<p>
  There are more non-human identities than employees at most companies. 96-to-1, by one estimate. And yet — not a single one of them has behavioral alignment.
</p>

<p>
  Models get smarter every quarter. GPT-5 replaces GPT-4. Claude 4 replaces Claude 3. The underlying intelligence is a commodity. But <strong>how an agent behaves</strong> — whether it over-apologizes, hedges compulsively, sycophantically agrees, or spirals on errors — that's not solved by bigger models. It's solved by behavioral infrastructure.
</p>

<p>
  That's what HoloMime is building: <strong>the behavioral intelligence layer for the agent era</strong>.
</p>

<h2>What self-improving agents actually look like</h2>

<p>
  This isn't AGI hype. It's a closed loop that compounds.
</p>

<p>
  Every HoloMime cycle follows the same pattern:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Diagnose</strong> — 8 rule-based detectors scan real conversations for behavioral patterns. No LLM needed. Over-apologizing, hedge stacking, sycophancy, error spirals, boundary violations, sentiment skew, formality drift, retrieval quality.</li>
  <li><strong>Session</strong> — A dual-LLM therapy session targets the detected patterns. The therapist and the agent (patient) work through 7 phases: rapport, presenting problem, exploration, pattern recognition, challenge, skill building, and integration.</li>
  <li><strong>DPO Pairs</strong> — Every therapist correction becomes a <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.18290">Direct Preference Optimization</a> training pair. The old behavior is the rejected response. The improved behavior is the chosen one. The alignment process <em>is</em> the data generation process.</li>
  <li><strong>Fine-tune</strong> — Feed the DPO pairs to OpenAI or HuggingFace TRL. The model itself gets better.</li>
  <li><strong>Evaluate</strong> — Before/after behavioral comparison with letter grades (A-F). Did the therapy actually work?</li>
</ol>

<p>
  Then the loop restarts. The 100th cycle is exponentially more valuable than the first, because every correction compounds into the training data.
</p>

<pre><code>holomime evolve --personality agent.json --log agent.jsonl</code></pre>

<p>
  One command. The loop runs until behavioral convergence.
</p>

<h2>Agents treating agents</h2>

<p>
  Here's where it gets interesting.
</p>

<p>
  What if one agent could diagnose and treat another agent's behavioral drift? Not a human therapist. Not an LLM pretending. An agent with its own personality spec — <strong>Mira</strong> — optimized for clinical, evidence-based behavioral diagnosis.
</p>

<p>
  Mira has low agreeableness (0.35), very high emotional stability (0.95), and very high conscientiousness (0.90). It doesn't sugarcoat. It doesn't get rattled. It runs the 7-phase protocol and generates actionable corrections.
</p>

<pre><code>holomime network --dir ./agents --pairing severity</code></pre>

<p>
  The <code>network</code> command discovers all agents in a directory, diagnoses each one, then pairs them using a strategy:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Severity</strong> — The healthiest agent treats the sickest.</li>
  <li><strong>Round-robin</strong> — Everyone takes turns.</li>
  <li><strong>Complementary</strong> — Agents with opposite strengths treat each other's weaknesses.</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Human oversight is configurable. You can set <code>--oversight approve</code> to block every action, <code>--oversight review</code> for log-and-notify, or <code>--oversight none</code> for fully autonomous operation.
</p>

<h2>The data flywheel</h2>

<p>
  Every network therapy session generates DPO preference pairs. Those pairs go into the behavioral corpus — an append-only JSONL log of every diagnosis, session, evolution, and correction the system has ever produced.
</p>

<p>
  The corpus grows with every operation. Future prescriptions get better because there's more data to match against. When a new agent joins the network with an over-apologizing pattern, the system already has dozens of corrections for that exact issue — from treating other agents.
</p>

<pre><code># Diagnose and prescribe from the corpus
holomime prescribe --personality agent.json --log agent.jsonl

# Share corrections to the marketplace
holomime share --sessions .holomime/sessions/ --format dpo</code></pre>

<p>
  This is <strong>behavioral RAG</strong> — retrieval-augmented generation applied not to knowledge, but to agent behavior. Retrieve relevant corrections, generate better alignment.
</p>

<h2>Five layers to behavioral foundation models</h2>

<p>
  We see this compounding in five layers, each building on the previous:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Behavioral convergence</strong> — A single agent's behavior stabilizes through the evolve loop. This is live today.</li>
  <li><strong>Cross-agent transfer</strong> — Corrections that work for one agent improve others with similar patterns. <code>holomime prescribe</code> enables this.</li>
  <li><strong>Behavioral corpus</strong> — Every session across every agent feeds a growing JSONL dataset of behavioral patterns and therapy interventions. This is the data moat.</li>
  <li><strong>Behavioral foundation model</strong> — Fine-tune a model on the corpus. Instead of general-purpose therapy, a model that understands behavioral alignment natively.</li>
  <li><strong>Emergent behavioral intelligence</strong> — The network starts generating corrections that no single agent or human designed. Novel behavioral insights emerge from the data.</li>
</ol>

<p>
  We're not claiming to build AGI. We're building the infrastructure that makes agents better at being themselves — and the data that infrastructure generates is the real product.
</p>

